1. Introduction, Model Choice & Dataset Justification 1a. Why are LDA and Sentiment Analysis the right approaches?

The client has two distinct operational needs: discovering what customers are writing about, and capturing how they feel emotionally. These requirements demand two different Natural Language Processing (NLP) families. Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA): LDA is an unsupervised generative probabilistic model that views documents as mixtures of topics, and topics as distributions over words. Because customer reviews on Hello Peter arrive as a messy library of unannotated free text where categories of complaints are unknown in advance, LDA serves as an automated thematic sorter. It looks at word co-occurrence frequencies to group terms into clear operational categories without needing expensive human pre-labeling

Sentiment Analysis via TextBlob & MultinomialNB: Sentiment analysis uses computational lexicons or text statistics to measure emotional orientation. By mapping free text onto a continuous scale from −1.0 (highly negative) to +1.0 (highly positive), the medical aid provider can accurately track corporate reputation trends.

Model Selection Comparison: While rule-based tools like VADER perform well on short social media text, TextBlob provides continuous polarity data ideal for creating categorical sentiment targets from structured reviews. When paired with Multinomial Naive Bayes (MNB) for classification, the pipeline handles feature spaces optimized by TF-IDF vectorization. MNB assumes discrete count logic—which fits sparse, heavily right-skewed text matrices perfectly—unlike Gaussian Naive Bayes, which expects symmetrical normal distributions.

Alternative Methods Counter-Justification: Alternative structural parsing frameworks like Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) drop distributional context in favor of linear matrix decomposition, resulting in polysemy errors and less interpretable topics. Non-Negative Matrix Factorization (NMF) creates rigid topic dimensions that are highly sensitive to small changes in vocabulary, making it less stable than LDA's flexible Dirichlet probabilistic priors.

