Justification of Model Choices LDA Choice: LDA was chosen over LSA because its probabilistic approach produces clear, interpretable word distributions rather than abstract linear factor components. This allows non-technical stakeholders to easily understand the core corporate issue behind each topic cluster.
Topic Count Selection: We chose a final model structure of 5 topics based on our perplexity analysis. Testing across broader categories showed diminishing returns beyond 5, where additional divisions only added noise without clarifying theme structures.

Sentiment Classifier Appropriateness: Because the raw text lacked pre-existing emotional labels, TextBlob provided an effective lexicon-driven baseline to programmatically generate targets. Training a supervised Multinomial Naive Bayes classifier on these targets allowed us to scale the analysis across our multi-word feature vectors.

Limitations & Future Enhancements: TextBlob relies on a static word library, meaning it can misclassify formal medical vocabulary or miss contextual shifts like sarcasm. If given more resources or a larger manually labeled dataset, we would replace the lexicon-driven framework with a fine-tuned Transformer model (such as DistilBERT) to better capture complex context and tone within the text.

Conclusion

The goal of this analysis was to identify why a medical aid provider is experiencing a surge in negative reviews on Hello Peter, using topic modeling and sentiment classification to uncover hidden patterns. Our text cleaning and preprocessing pipeline successfully isolated core terms by removing generic industry noise words. The final LDA model revealed 5 clear areas of concern for the client: Claims Processing Delays, Frontline Customer Service, Chronic Medication Exclusions, Digital Platform Stability, and Call Center Operational Friction. The sentiment analysis confirmed that half of all logged customer feedback is negative, driven primarily by operational delays and benefit exclusions. Cross-referencing our models showed that Claims Processing Delays (Topic 1) and Call Center Operational Friction (Topic 5) generate entirely negative reviews, indicating these backend bottlenecks are the true cause of customer dissatisfaction. To improve customer retention, management should focus on automating low-risk claims and optimizing call center routing to resolve high-risk complaints before they lead to cancellations.

